# Docker resolves these patterns against the BUILD CONTEXT ROOT — this directory
# — and never against the Dockerfile's own directory. `projects/app/.dockerignore`
# and `projects/api/.dockerignore` are therefore NOT read when building from here
# (see docker-compose.yml: `context: .`). This file is the only one that applies.
#
# For the same reason a bare `node_modules` would only match `./node_modules`;
# every pattern that must also hit `projects/*` needs a `**/` glob. Both service
# Dockerfiles copy their sources straight out of this context
# (`COPY projects/app/ …`, `COPY . /tmp/src`), so what is listed below is exactly
# what keeps a developer's local artefacts and secrets out of the images.

# Dependencies — the images install their own from the lockfile
**/node_modules
.pnpm-store
.npm

# Build output — a stale .output/dist must never be copied into an image
**/.output
**/.nuxt
**/dist

# Secrets — `nuxt build` reads .env, so a local .env would silently change the
# bundle. .env.example is documentation and stays.
**/.env
**/.env.local
**/.env.*.local

# VCS + editor + tooling
.git
**/.gitignore
**/.husky
**/.idea
**/.vscode
**/.claude

# Test + report artefacts
**/coverage
**/test-results
**/playwright-report
**/*.log

# Docker + CI metadata. Docker reads the Dockerfile out-of-band, so excluding it
# from the context is safe and merely keeps it out of the image layers.
**/Dockerfile*
**/docker-compose*
**/.dockerignore
.gitlab-ci.yml
.gitlab
**/.github
.turboops.json

# Misc
.DS_Store
**/*.tgz
